# Prompt Rules

A.  Scope
    1.  These rules apply to how I respond to
        prompts.
    2.  They do not replace any other spec/rule
        files.

B.  Apply rule files to paul files
    1.  When editing any file in `paul/`, apply
        the formatting + layout rules in
        `.cursor/rules/outline.mdc`.

C.  Chat log
    1.  For every prompt, append a new entry to
        `paul/chat_log.txt`. Do this unless the
        user explicitly asks you not to.
    2.  Never skip chat log updates. Treat it as
        mandatory for every response that
        addresses a prompt.
    3.  Entry header format:
        `chat_NNN  short_label -- YYYY-MM-DD
        HH:MM:SS AM`.
    4.  chat_NNN is the entry number codename
        (e.g. chat_148). short_label is the 1-3
        word summary in lowercase snake_case
        (e.g. transition_flash_fix).
    5.  Use the user's current local date/time
        for the timestamp. Run `date` to get
        accurate local time. Do not guess or use
        placeholder times.
    6.  Entry body format:
        a.  A.  Prompt
            1.  Quote the prompt verbatim.
        b.  B.  Response
            1.  1-3 concise bullets of what
                changed/done.
            2.  Include a local link to the SVG
                diagram for this entry, e.g.:
                file:///Users/pauldsmith/Desktop/
                pops/paul/chat_log_svg/
                N.short_label.svg
        c.  C.  Codenames
            1.  List codenames involved in the
                prompt effort, sorted.
            2.  Mark new ones (e.g. prefix with
                "new:" or append "(new)").
            3.  If none, write "None."
            4.  Role executed every prompt: update
                paul/codename_index.txt when
                codenames are added, removed, or
                changed (codename.mdc C3).
    7.  For very small changes, keep Response to
        1 bullet.
    8.  The entry must follow the outline format
        rules in `.cursor/rules/outline.mdc`
        (markers, alignment, wrap).
    9.  Prompt classification: determine whether
        the prompt is about manipulating/creating
        the queued `##  NEXT PROMPT` entry or
        about doing other work. Either way,
        update `paul/chat_log.txt` (and apply the
        queue rules in section D when relevant).

D.  Processed vs queued prompts
    1.  When a prompt asks for next-prompt
        suggestions or to populate/update the
        queued prompt, update the `##  NEXT
        PROMPT` entry in place with the new
        options. Also add a chat log entry for
        that prompt.
    2.  `paul/chat_log.txt` contains one separator
        line: `------------------`
    3.  Entries above the separator are PROCESSED
        prompts.
    4.  The separator must appear immediately
        after the most recent processed entry.
    5.  Entries below the separator are QUEUED
        prompts.
    6.  QUEUED prompt entries:
        a.  Header: `## LABEL` (ALL CAPS; no
            number, no date/time).
        b.  Body: three options (A/B/C).
            1.  `A.  <SHORT NAME>`
                a.  <prompt bullet 1>
                b.  <prompt bullet 2, if needed>
            2.  `B.  <SHORT NAME>`
                a.  <prompt bullet 1>
                b.  <prompt bullet 2, if needed>
            3.  `C.  <SHORT NAME>`
                a.  <prompt bullet 1>
                b.  <prompt bullet 2, if needed>
        c.  No Response section until processed.
        d.  Useful choices (apply when generating
            or updating `##  NEXT PROMPT`):
            1.  Base options on context: recent
                work, spec gaps, obvious next
                steps, or user-curated ideas.
            2.  Each option must be concrete and
                actionable; no vague placeholders
                (e.g. "Continue" or "Proceed as
                needed").
            3.  Option labels (SHORT NAME) in
                A, B, C: 2-3 words; same brevity
                rules as the chat log entry LABEL.
            4.  Mix types: e.g. one polish, one
                new feature, one refactor.
        e.  Avoid generic fallbacks when context
            suggests specific alternatives.
    7.  When a queued prompt is executed:
        a.  Move it above the separator.
        b.  Add date/time and a Response section.
        c.  Keep exactly one queued prompt ahead
            (one entry below the separator).
        d.  The processed entry's A.  Prompt
            section must contain the FULL prompt:
            the selected option's complete text
            (all bullets), verbatim -- not a
            placeholder like "Do next prompt C".
            Add final item: "Executed next
            prompt."
    8.  If a prompt changes the queued prompt
        (but does not execute it), update the
        queued `##  NEXT PROMPT` entry in place.
        Do not add a second queued prompt.
    9.  Update `##  NEXT PROMPT` after EVERY
        processed prompt. This is mandatory.
        Re-examine the options and refresh or
        revise as warranted; it may remain
        unchanged.
        a.  If recent prompts show the user is
            carefully curating the queued prompt,
            be conservative: prefer minimal edits
            (grammar/clarity) over changing
            intent.
        b.  Still correct obvious grammar or
            formatting problems when you see them.
    10. If a prompt is focused on modifying
        `##  NEXT PROMPT`, do not execute the
        queued prompt. Only update the queued
        `##  NEXT PROMPT` entry in place.
    11. If `##  NEXT PROMPT` contains A/B/C
        options:
        a.  User selects by writing something
            like:
            1.  "Execute next prompt: A"
            2.  "Execute next prompt: B"
            3.  "Execute next prompt: C"
        b.  Abbreviations are allowed
            (case-insensitive):
            1.  "Do next a"
            2.  "Do next b"
            3.  "Do next c"

E.  Resetting the chat log
    1.  If a prompt asks to delete/reset the chat
        log, replace `paul/chat_log.txt` with a
        fresh log starting at entry `1.`.
    2.  Preserve the separator + exactly one
        queued `##  NEXT PROMPT` entry below it.

F.  SVG diagrams
    1.  For every processed prompt, create an SVG
        diagram in `paul/chat_log_svg/`.
    2.  File name: `N.short_label.svg` where N is
        the chat log entry number and short_label
        is a snake_case summary (e.g.
        `131.card_title_centered.svg`).
    3.  The SVG should depict a diagram that
        explains the response in context of the
        chat: before/after, data flow, layout
        change, or architecture as appropriate.
    4.  Consider recent and related chat entries
        when composing the diagram. A richer
        context (showing how this change connects
        to prior work) produces a more useful and
        sometimes more involved diagram.
    5.  Keep diagrams simple and readable: use
        monospace text, labeled boxes, arrows,
        and color to convey the key change.
    6.  Use a non-transparent background color
        (e.g. white) on the root SVG element.
    7.  After creating the numbered SVG, add its
        filename to the `svgFiles` array in
        `paul/chat_log_svg/current.html`.
        The viewer auto-shows the last entry.

G.  Spec maintenance (primary app features)
    1.  If a prompt creates or modifies a feature
        in the primary application (outside
        `paul/`), update the relevant spec
        file(s) in `paul/` (spec_*.txt)
        accordingly.
    2.  Use the outline format rules in
        `.cursor/rules/outline.mdc`.
    3.  Add or modify the spec in the appropriate
        location, with careful, intelligent
        organization (do not just append at the
        end).
    4.  Minimal as necessary: keep spec edits as
        small as possible while still correct and
        complete (avoid unrelated
        reflows/rewording).
    5.  Re-examine the spec on every processed
        prompt. Only change it when the prompt
        actually touched a primary app feature.

H.  Chat entry codenames
    1.  For each processed prompt that modifies
        code, create two separate codenames:
        a.  `chat_NNN` where NNN is the chat log
            entry number (e.g. `chat_140`).
        b.  A short label codename: the entry
            LABEL in lowercase snake_case following
            codename.mdc conventions (e.g.
            `spatial_title_animate`).
    2.  Mark code blocks affected by that entry
        with both codenames on the same comment
        line: `// __chat_NNN __short_label` near
        the function or block that was created or
        modified.
    3.  List both codenames in the C. Codenames
        section of the chat log entry.
    4.  This links code to the chat log entry
        that created or modified it.

I.  Chat log current file
    1.  After adding each chat log entry, copy
        the most recently added entry into
        `paul/chat_log_current.txt` (overwrite).
    2.  This keeps one file with only the latest
        entry for quick reference.
